/  == root
# Linux Command Notes

## 1. ls
Description: List files and directories in the current directory.

Examples:
ls                   # List files in the current directory
ls -l                 # List in long format (with details)
ls -R                 # List files and directories recursive
ls *.txt              # List files matching *.txt
ls [ab].txt          # List files matching a.txt or b.txt
ls [!ab]*            # List files NOT starting with a or b


## 2. cd
Description: Change directory.

Examples:
cd directory_name    # Change to directory_name
cd ..                 # Change to parent directory
cd /absolute/path    # Change to an absolute path
cd                   # Change to home directory


## 3. pwd
Description: Prints the current directory.

Example:
pwd                   # Prints working directory


## 4. touch
Description: Create a new, empty file.

Examples:
touch a.txt
touch b.txt
touch new{1..4}.txt   # Create new1.txt, new2.txt, new3.txt, new4.txt


## 5. mkdir
Description: Create a directory.

Examples:
mkdir test
mkdir -p course/che/projectOfChe


## 6. rmdir
Description: Remove a directory (directory must be empty).

Examples:
rmdir testdel
rmdir LPU


## 7. rm
Description: Remove files or directories.

Examples:
rm a.txt               # Remove a file
rm *.txt               # Remove multiple files matching pattern
rm -r directory_name   # Remove directory and its content


## 8. cp
Description: Copy files or directories.

Examples:
cp a.txt b.txt                   # Copy a.txt to b.txt
cp lpu*.txt Documents/          # Copy files matching pattern to directory
cp -r alpha/ Documents/        # Recursively copy directory


## 9. mv
Description: Move or rename files or directories.

Examples:
mv new3.txt new3(updated).txt   # Renaming a file
mv lpu*.txt Music/              # Move files matching pattern into directory


## 10. history
Description: Prints previously used commands.

Example:
history                   # Prints command history


## Additional Notes:

- * : match ANY number of ANY character
- ? : match ANY single character
- [abc] : match ANY character within brackets
- [!abc] : match ANY character except those listed
- {1..10} : expansion of range (creates multiple files or directories)


